natural problem: A square has an area of $25.$ A rectangle has the same width as the square. The length of the rectangle is double its width. What is the area of the rectangle?
natural solution: For the square to have an area of $25,$ each side length must be $\sqrt{25}=5.$ The rectangle's width is equal to that of the square and therefore must also be $5.$ The length of the rectangle is double its width or $5\times 2=10.$ The area of the rectangle is thus $5\times 10=\boxed{50}.$

assumes h0 : "S = 25"

shows  "R = 50"
